{"actual_usd":0.15962500000000002,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":254,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31163,"reply":"\"Hm— yeah, those are the two big naturalistic lanes people usually reach for.\" *I push my glasses up and squint a little into the morning light off the square stones.* \"Grief-visions can explain an experience here or there, but they have a hard time carrying the whole shape of the claim — multiple people, stubborn public proclamation, the empty-tomb part if you grant it, and a movement that didn’t sound like, 'We had a powerful sense he was still with us,' but, 'God raised him.'\"\n\n*I hook a thumb against the edge of the bench, thinking.* \"And the 'didn’t really die' route always feels weaker to me. The Romans knew how to kill people. A half-dead Jesus limping out of a tomb doesn’t really produce resurrection faith anyway — that gives you 'he survived,' not 'he conquered death.'\"\n\n\"I'm not saying naturalistic proposals are stupid. Just that they usually explain one slice by thinning out the rest.\" *I glance back at you.* \"For me the real question is which account best explains why those first witnesses talked the way they did. Do you mean historically, or more at the level of what you yourself can honestly believe?\"","rolling_24h_usd":69.97641999999999,"run_id":"b63a44e2-3fdf-4ae1-ac89-74f6e4b5aac1"}
